lacename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Wineca</i> + Old English <i>wīc</i>.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Winnik</b>, an occupational name for a wine seller, from Polish <i>wino</i> ‘wine’ + the agent suffix <i>-nik</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Winwick was born about 1139, in Whittingham, Lancashire, England, his father, Robert de Winwick, was 111 and his mother, Lady Elizabeth Winwick, was 109. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1194, at the age of 56."},"et":{"Abt 1139–1194":"umbes 1139–1194","1055–1100":"1055–1100","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1139–1194":"1139–1194","1162–1215":"1162–1215","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1165–1215":"1165–1215","1029–Male":"1029–Surnud","1032–Female":"1032–Surnud","1029":"1029","1139":"1139","1215":"1215","b